                </cit>
        </cit>
        <etym xml:lang="ru">Из %ikan%i, ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kættag"/> ‘полотно’ из
                %ikæn-tag%i. Ближайшие соответствия в сванском и абхазском: <mentioned
                        xml:lang="sva"><lang/><w>kan</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ab"
                                ><lang/><w>a-k˳nə</w><gloss><q>конопля</q></gloss></mentioned>. Сюда
                же, может быть, <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"
                                ><lang/><w>ganä</w><gloss><q>рубашка</q></gloss></mentioned>. Слово
                идентично, очевидно, с первой частью широко распространенного названия конопли:
                        <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>κάνναβις</w></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="la"><lang/><w>cannabis</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang=""
                                ><lang/><w>конопля</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bg"
                                ><lang/><w>коноп</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cs"
                                ><lang/><w>konopě</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="pl"
                                ><lang/><w>konop</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note
                                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned><mentioned
                        xml:lang="pl"><w>konopie</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note
                                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned>, , <mentioned
                        xml:lang="goh"><lang/><w>hana</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"
                                ><lang/><w>Hanf</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                                ><lang/><w>kanab, kana</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="zkh"
                                ><lang/><w>knb</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
                                ><lang/><w>купр’</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
                                ><lang/><w>kumbā, kanbā</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xcl"
                                ><lang/><w>kʼanap</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
                                ><lang/><w>kʼanapi</w></mentioned> и др. Свидетельство %sГеродота%s
                                (<bibl><biblScope>Геродот</biblScope></bibl>) и %sГесихия%s
                                (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Гесихий"/></bibl>), что конопля
                (%iκάνναβις%i) — скифское растение, а также другие соображения заставляют искать
                родину его названия в восточной Европе. Об этом говорит и наличие простой формы
                названия конопли в %bмарийском%b языке: <mentioned xml:lang="chm"><lang/><w>kene,
                                kəne</w></mentioned>. %sSchrader%s (<bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Schrader"/><biblScope>440 сл.</biblScope></bibl>)
                полагает, что греческое название %iκάνναβις%i есть скрещение двух
                восточноевропейских названий этого растения: %ikana%i (<mentioned xml:lang="chm"
                                ><lang/><w>kene</w></mentioned>) и %ipiš%i (<mentioned xml:lang=""
                                ><lang/><w>pəš</w></mentioned>). Ос. %igæn%i, %i*kæn%i позволяет
                думать, что в скифском также существовала простая форма %i*kana%i. Этот же элемент
                налицо в %bтюркских%b названиях конопли <mentioned xml:lang="trk"
                                ><lang/><w>ken-dir</w></mentioned> (во второй части <mentioned
                        xml:lang="trk"><lang/><w>tiri,
                        diri</w><gloss><q>жесткий</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="trk"
                                        ><w/><gloss><q>грубый</q></gloss></mentioned>, ?).
                Осетинское выражение %igænyston fæu!%i „чтоб тебе зарасти коноплей!“ (о каком-либо
                месте) звучит как проклятие. Это говорит о том, что в староосетинском речь шла о
                дикой конопле, которая рассматривалась как сорняк и была символом
                запустения.[[Аналогично в русском: „В больничном дворе стоит небольшой флигель,
                окруженный целым лесом репейника, крапивы и дикой конопли“ (<bibl><biblScope
                                xml:lang="ru">А. П. Чехов. Палата № 6. Собр. соч., т. 7, М., 1956,
                                стр. 121</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">A. P. Chekhov. Ward No.
                                6. The Works by A.P. Chekhov, Vol. 7, Moscow., 1956, p.
                                121</biblScope></bibl>).]] Ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kættag"
                                />.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Munkácsi._Alan."
                                /><biblScope>327</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Jacobsohn"/><biblScope xml:lang="ru">91
                                сл.</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">91 ff.</biblScope></bibl> —
                                <bibl><ref target="#ref_Sköld._Oss."/><biblScope xml:lang="ru">103
                                сл.</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">103 ff.</biblScope></bibl>
                                —<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>60, 170, 198, 296,
                                312</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
        <etym xml:lang="en">From %ikan%i, compare with <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kættag"/>
                ‘linen’ from %ikæn-tag%i. The closest correspondences are found in Svan and Abkhaz:
                        <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/><w>kan</w></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ab"
                ><lang/><w>a-k˳nə</w><gloss><q>cannabis</q></gloss></mentioned>. Maybe <mentioned
                        xml:lang="kbd"><lang/><w>ganä</w><gloss><q>shirt</q></gloss></mentioned> is
                related to it as well. The word is obviously identical to the first part of a
                widespread cannabis name: <mentioned xml:lang="grc"
                        ><lang/><w>κάνναβις</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"
                                ><lang/><w>cannabis</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang=""
                                ><lang/><w>конопля</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bg"
                                ><lang/><w>коноп</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cs"
                                ><lang/><w>konopě</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="pl"
                                ><lang/><w>konop</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note
                                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned><mentioned
                        xml:lang="pl"><w>konopie</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note
                                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned>, , <mentioned
                        xml:lang="goh"><lang/><w>hana</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"
                                ><lang/><w>Hanf</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                                ><lang/><w>kanab, kana</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="zkh"
                                ><lang/><w>knb</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
                                ><lang/><w>купр’</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
                                ><lang/><w>kumbā, kanbā</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="xcl"
                                ><lang/><w>kʼanap</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
                                ><lang/><w>kʼanapi</w></mentioned> etc. The evidence of
                                <bibl><author>Herodotus</author></bibl>and <bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Гесихий"/></bibl> that cannabis (%iκάνναβις%i) is a
                Scythian plant, and also some other reasons force to look for the homeland of its
                name in Eastern Europe. This is also evidenced by the presence of a simple form of
                the name of cannabis in %bMari%b language: <mentioned xml:lang="chm"><lang/><w>kene,
                                kəne</w></mentioned>. %sSchrader%s (<bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Schrader"/><biblScope>440f.</biblScope></bibl>)
                supposes that a Greek name %iκάνναβις%i is a crossover of two Eastern European names
                of this plant: %ikana%i (<mentioned xml:lang="chm"><lang/><w>kene</w></mentioned>)
                and %ipiš%i (<mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w>pəš</w></mentioned>). Ossetic %igæn%i,
                %i*kæn%i allows to think that in Scythian there also was a simple form %i*kana%i.
                The same element is present in the %bTurkic%b names of cannabis <mentioned
                        xml:lang="trk"><lang/><w>ken-dir</w></mentioned> (is there <mentioned
                        xml:lang="trk"><lang/><w>tiri,
                        diri</w><gloss><q>coarse</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="trk"
                                        ><w/><gloss><q>rough</q></gloss></mentioned>, in the second
                part of the word?). The Ossetic expression %igænyston fæu!%i “so that you are
                overgrown with cannabis!” (about some place) sounds like a curse. This suggests that
                in Old Ossetiс it was about wild cannabis, which was considered as a weed and was a
                symbol of desolation.<note n="1"> PUT NOTE HERE </note> Compare with <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_kættag"/>.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Munkácsi._Alan."
                                /><biblScope>327</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Jacobsohn"/><biblScope xml:lang="ru">91
                                сл.</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">91 ff.</biblScope></bibl> —
                                <bibl><ref target="#ref_Sköld._Oss."/><biblScope xml:lang="ru">103
                                сл.</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">103 ff.</biblScope></bibl>
                                —<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>60, 170, 198, 296,
                                312</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
